In Antwarp 11yer
S my last to you was on the 4 curitt sence recd. yd of 2½ past dy
which I perceant that yd cloth maker would faine have 20 st p cloth
more thought he is bovund to delives, you whath he hath promised
I hope you shall secure the 10p. of £9: & the £10:of £10: as you
writt mee the 31: of Ianu last butt in case you van nott I shall
content mij self with 10 peeces viz 5 of each which might
be one bale, besides you please to buy 3 of £8: & 2 aurovas of
£15:10 a £12 ap. which will be 5p to make an other bale
I exspect dayly to heare from John nelson, whom I wish migh
be prived by this time, as soone I see those goodds & that
I finde that cloth so content, shall in order a good parceel
to be provided in may & I une next, where fore itt will not
beamis, that you p lease to in forme mee how goods rule
in the north, as also spanish cloathes in London, iintending
do send you some pattarnes p: first to have a small purcell
from thene whilst I remaine with my heartykernue
In Antwaris 17 march
London Henry maynard
S my last to you was on the 8: curitt sence recd. yd of 25 past my
t hanckes for accepting my sundry bills, & seeng you are not pleased with
so doing, butt for bidd itt, I'll do itt no more thought Ik neder refusd
itt to his correspondents up on such occasion, whoever I'll pleased
you & without any faile remitt you the valew, be fore due day
on which you may depend, as alss for more for my acctt. & where
as I observe that the last parcell of gold did afford no proffitt,
shall onely be a remitting for yd acctt. as the ex ruleth: butt where
as you feare, that ex will rise more so I should concli de this
the gold would rise accordingly: where fore the proffitt by that woud
bethe more: please to take noticie, that about this time our
customers from out of towne come to mackett, principally the
walloones & bring mucth gold in spetie with them which they pince
up on us & pay att the rate of the least parcell, & att present have
about £400: in gold flom: amonghst which about 30 bo oad peeces
of ƒ12: & ƒ23 ap. so shall dispose of that for silves mony oneles
you please I send itt to you for yd accompt, where fore shall keep
itt by mee till yd answer here unto, which please to returne govery
first I shall peruse the pattarnes you sent mee & seeng you call
my patt. I sent for instructions, dull coad cullours pray suy some to yd
fancy & when the number of 60 p is compleated, desist till
fuither order, so that there is butt 12 p. of them wanting I do not
know whether my formars shall prove to yd content as for the
continuancy of our comp. because you doso much persitt in
complaints & you do not once con sidder that the comp accompt of
charges from 1680 I anu till udr. june following is chearged witt
ƒ561:10 for scoureing the debts till that day which & the dini
nition of our charges on this side will come, or make ourgaine
now easely 13 a 14 pt. besides our debts ore not so imsertaine as you
imagin, for god be thancked I have not one pound standing outt of 1679
so that all the debts I have are made 1680, & the present whoever you
will finde mee ready to comply with you as you can reasonabley
propose for be confident I do not intend to trade for pleasure, or
the name of itt, & when I can make 20 p.c. for my mony, shall
not do itt less, butt the worst of all is that what one doth not, an other
doth, so that the ganes are brought low: John veele sells so cheap his spanees
cloathes att brussel, that I can nott sell any thingh there Ik sents so
good goods to his freinds here as well northren goods as london that when
